  \cf5 Java's Philosophy on I/O: Optimistic vs Defensive\cf2  \
 \
  JavaScript says: "Try the I/O operation, deal with errors if they happen." \
  Java says: "Before you even compile, prove to me you have a plan for when \
  this fails." \
 \
  This is checked exceptions in action. File operations declare \cf11 throws \cf2  \
  IOException in their signature - it's a compile-time contract that says \
  "this can fail in ways beyond your control." The compiler won't let you \
  ignore this. \
 \
  Why? Because in production, I/O failures are NORMAL: \
  - Disks fill up \
  - Permissions change \
  - Networks hiccup \
  - Hardware fails \
 \
  JavaScript makes it easy to ship code that crashes mysteriously at 3am. \
  Java makes it impossible to compile that code in the first place. \
  \cf11 \uc0\u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \u9472 \cf2  \
